  "prompt": "How is the square root of 50 simplified?",
  "response": "To simplify the square root of 50, you want to express it in the form of \\(\\sqrt{a \\times b}\\) where either \\(a\\) or \\(b\\) is a perfect square. The number 50 can be factored into 25 and 2:\n\n\\[\n50 = 25 \\times 2\n\\]\n\nTherefore,\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt{50} = \\sqrt{25 \\times 2}\n\\]\n\nUsing the property of square roots that \\(\\sqrt{a \\times b} = \\sqrt{a} \\times \\sqrt{b}\\), we get:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt{50} = \\sqrt{25} \\times \\sqrt{2}\n\\]\n\nSince \\(\\sqrt{25} = 5\\), this simplifies to:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt{50} = 5 \\times \\sqrt{2}\n\\]\n\nSo, the square root of 50 simplified is:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt{50} = 5\\sqrt{2}\n\\]",
